parameters.description:
An ordered list of edits applied to one workbook. Each entry is an object whose "type" selects which other fields are read; fields that don't belong to the type are ignored. Operations run in order and the batch is non-atomic (up to 50 operations sharing a ~25s budget), so inspect operation_results to confirm each one landed.

DEFAULT QUALITY: when creating a workbook for a person to read, produce a clean, professional table by default rather than a bare value dump. The reliable recipe is: write typed values, turn the data into a native Excel table with a restrained built-in style, apply appropriate number formats, and ALWAYS resize columns so every header and label is fully readable. Keep sheet names and headers plain text (no emojis) unless asked. Only skip the polish when the user asks for raw data or a specific style.

RESIZING IS MANDATORY (agents usually skip this — do not): after writing values, end the same call with format_columns autofit=true over every column that has content (e.g. "A:D"). Default column widths leave long labels truncated (#### or cut off in the UI). Autofit is the required fix; if a label is still clipped after autofit, follow up with an explicit column_width (points) on that column. Never ship a user-facing workbook without a resizing step.

Professional table (the default recipe for tabular data — one set_values write, then styling; the last op MUST autofit):
[{"type": "set_values", "worksheet": "Sales", "values_csv": "Region,Units,Revenue\nEast,120,15000\nWest,90,11800\nNorth,75,9600"}, {"type": "add_table", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "A1:C4", "has_header": true, "table_style": "TableStyleMedium2", "show_banded_rows": true, "show_filter_button": true}, {"type": "format_columns", "worksheet": "Sales", "columns": "C:C", "number_format": "$#,##0"}, {"type": "format_columns", "worksheet": "Sales", "columns": "A:C", "autofit": true}]

VALUES AND FORMATTING ARE SEPARATE STEPS: one operation does not carry both cell values and their formatting. Write the data with set_values, then style it with add_table / format_columns / format_cells in later operations of the same call. Autofit must be its own format_columns operation after the values exist — sizing before set_values does nothing useful.

set_values — write typed values and formulas. Prefer values_csv (or values_tsv) for a plain grid; numbers and booleans in the text are stored as such, and a cell beginning with = is a formula. If a value contains the delimiter — e.g. a comma inside a formula like =SUM(A1,B1) when using values_csv — use values_tsv or the values JSON form so it is not split into separate cells. Anchor at the top-left of range if given, else A1:
{"type": "set_values", "worksheet": "Q1", "values_csv": "Item,Price,Qty,Total\nPen,1.5,10,=B2*C2\nPad,3.25,4,=B3*C3"}
Use values (a JSON-encoded 2D-array string) when you need exact typing, e.g. to keep a leading-zero code as text:
{"type": "set_values", "worksheet": "Q1", "range": "A1", "values": "[[\"SKU\",\"Qty\"],[\"007\",12]]"}

append_rows — add rows after the current used range (rows is a JSON-encoded 2D array):
{"type": "append_rows", "worksheet": "Log", "rows": "[[\"2024-05-01\", 42]]"}

format_cells — style a range: bold, italic, font_color, font_size, fill_color, horizontal_alignment (Left/Center/Right), vertical_alignment (Top/Center/Bottom), border_style, wrap_text, row_height, and number_format. Colors are hex like #4472C4:
{"type": "format_cells", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "A1:C1", "bold": true, "fill_color": "#4472C4", "font_color": "#FFFFFF", "horizontal_alignment": "Center"}
{"type": "format_cells", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "C2:C100", "number_format": "$#,##0.00"}
Number-format codes are standard Excel: "#,##0" (grouped integer), "0.00%" (percent), "$#,##0.00" (currency), "yyyy-mm-dd" (date), "@" (force text).

format_columns — ALWAYS autofit (or set an explicit column_width) on every used column before finishing a create/edit for a human reader; also apply number_format down whole columns when needed. Target with columns like "A:D" (or range). Autofit example (required closing step of the default recipe):
{"type": "format_columns", "worksheet": "Sales", "columns": "A:D", "autofit": true}
Number-format-only example:
{"type": "format_columns", "worksheet": "Sales", "columns": "B:B", "number_format": "0.00%"}

add_table — turn a range into a native Excel table, which gives a styled header, banding, and filter buttons. has_header defaults to true; table_style is a built-in name like "TableStyleMedium2". Set show_totals to add a totals row below the table (Excel totals the last column by default) when the data has a column worth totaling:
{"type": "add_table", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "A1:D20", "table_style": "TableStyleMedium2", "show_banded_rows": true, "show_filter_button": true}

sort — reorder rows by one column; has_header keeps the first row in place:
{"type": "sort", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "A1:D20", "sort_key_column": "C", "sort_order": "descending", "has_header": true}

add_chart — build a chart from a data range and place it with anchor_cell (plus optional end_cell to size it); title, legend_position, value_axis_title, and category_axis_title refine it:
{"type": "add_chart", "worksheet": "Sales", "range": "A1:B5", "chart_type": "ColumnClustered", "title": "Revenue by region", "anchor_cell": "F2", "end_cell": "L20"}

Other operations use the same object shape, selected by type: clear, merge, unmerge, insert_rows, delete_rows, insert_columns, delete_columns, add_worksheet, delete_worksheet, update_worksheet, duplicate_worksheet, update_table, delete_table, update_chart, delete_chart, add_named_range, delete_named_range, protect_worksheet, unprotect_worksheet, recalculate.

Not available as operations: conditional formatting, data-validation dropdowns, and frozen panes. A workbook that needs those must be built as a complete .xlsx file and uploaded, rather than assembled from these operations.

Ranges are bounded A1 (e.g. "A1:D10"). Each operation may name its own worksheet; if omitted, the call's default worksheet is used.
